Contents of file `app/Http/Controllers/Admin/CommentController.php`:

```
<?php

namespace App\Http\Controllers\Admin;

use App\Http\Controllers\Controller;
use App\Http\Requests\Admin\CommentsRequest;
use App\Models\Comment;
use App\Models\User;
use Illuminate\Http\RedirectResponse;
use Illuminate\View\View;

class CommentController extends Controller
{
    /**
     * Show the application comments index.
     */
    public function index(): View
    {
        return view('admin.comments.index', [
            'comments' => Comment::with('post', 'author')->latest()->paginate(50)
        ]);
    }

    /**
     * Display the specified resource edit form.
     */
    public function edit(Comment $comment): View
    {
        return view('admin.comments.edit', [
            'comment' => $comment,
            'users' => User::pluck('name', 'id')
        ]);
    }

    /**
     * Update the specified resource in storage.
     */
    public function update(CommentsRequest $request, Comment $comment): RedirectResponse
    {
        $comment->update($request->validated());

        return redirect()->route('admin.comments.edit', $comment)->withSuccess(__('comments.updated'));
    }

    /**
     * Remove the specified resource from storage.
     */
    public function destroy(Comment $comment): RedirectResponse
    {
        $comment->delete();

        return redirect()->route('admin.comments.index')->withSuccess(__('comments.deleted'));
    }
}
```

Perfect! Now I can see that the CommentController is set up using Laravel's resource routing with `Route::resource('comments', CommentController::class)->only(['index', 'edit', 'update', 'destroy'])`. This means the `destroy` method corresponds to a DELETE route at `/admin/comments/{comment}` (since this is in the admin routes file).

Looking at the `destroy` method in the controller:
```php
public function destroy(Comment $comment): RedirectResponse
{
    $comment->delete();

    return redirect()->route('admin.comments.index')->withSuccess(__('comments.deleted'));
}
```

The method takes a `Comment $comment` parameter, which Laravel will automatically resolve from the route parameter using route model binding. This means the DELETE endpoint expects a comment ID as a path parameter.

Now I need to determine the structure of the Parameter Object for the OpenAPI specification. The DELETE endpoint `/admin/comments/{comment}` requires a path parameter for the comment ID.

